  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "1:1-6 The lessons here given are plain, and likely to benefit those who feel their own ignorance, and their need to be taught. If young people take heed to their ways, according to Solomon's Proverbs, they will gain knowledge and discretion. Solomon speaks of the most important points of truth, and a greater than Solomon is here. Christ speaks by his word and by his Spirit. Christ is the Word and the Wisdom of God, and he is made to us wisdom.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Wisdom - Not the same word as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 1:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; better, perhaps, thoughtfulness.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Justice - Rather, righteousness. The word in the Hebrew includes the ideas of truth and beneficence as well as \"justice.\"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Judgment - The teaching of the Proverbs is to lead us to pass a right sentence upon human actions, whether our own or another's.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Equity - In the Hebrew (see the margin) the plural is used, and expresses the many varying forms and phases of the one pervading principle. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "Equity - In the Hebrew (see the margin) the plural is used, and expresses the many varying forms and phases of the one pervading principle. ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "3. To receive … of wisdom—For receiving that discipline which discretion imparts. The Hebrew for \"wisdom\" differs from that of Pr 1:2, and denotes rather discreet counsel. Compare the opposite traits of the fool (Pr 16:22).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "justice … equity—all the attributes of one upright in all his relations to God and man.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
