  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 3.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "To receive the instruction of wisdom.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " This verse carries on the statement of the design of the Proverbs. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "To receive",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; Hebrew, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "לְקַחַת",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "lakakhath",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), not the same word as \"to know\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "לָדַּעַת",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), in ver. 2, though regarded as synonymous with it by Delitzsch. Its meaning is well represented by the LXX. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "δέξασθαι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and the Authorized Version \"to receive.\" The Hebrew, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "לָקַחַת",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", is infinitive, and means properly \"to take, or lay hold of,\" hence \"to receive,\" Greek, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "δέχομαι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", No doubt it conveys the idea of intellectual reception (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 2:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "The instruction of wisdom",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; Hebrew, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "מוּסַר הַשְׂכֵּל",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "musar has'kel",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "); ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the discipline or moral training which leads on to reason, intelligence, or wisdom (as Hitzig, Fuerst, Zockler); or discipline full of insight, discernment, or thoughtfulness (as Umbreit, Ewald, Delitzsch). The phrase does not mean the wisdom which instruction imparts. The ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "word musar",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " occurs here in a slightly different sense from its use in ver. 2; there it is objective, here its meaning as a medium for the attainment of wisdom is more distinctly brought out. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Wisdom",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "haskel",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "is",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " properly \"thoughtfulness\" (so Umbreit. Ewald, Delitzsch, Plumptre). It is strictly the infinitive absolute of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "שָׂכַל",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "sakal",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), \"to entwine or involve,\" and as a substantive it stands for the thinking through of a subject, so \"thoughtfulness.\" The LXX. renders this sentence, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "δέξασθαί τε στροφὰς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", which St. Jerome understands as \"versutias sermonum et solutiones aenigmatum\" (\"the cunning or craftiness of words and the explication of enigmas\"). ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Justice, and judgment, and equity.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " These words seem to be the unfolding of the meaning contained in the expression, \"the instruction of wisdom.\" Holden regards the last four words as objective genitives dependent on \"instruction,\" but wrongly. Cornelius a Laplde states that \"justice and judgment and equity\" indicate the same thing in different aspects. \"",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Justice",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " stands for the thing itself - that which is ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "just",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "judgment",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in respect of right reason, which says it is just; and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "equity",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in respect of its being agreeable to the Law of God.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "Justice",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; Hebrew, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "צֶדֶק",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "tsedek",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), from the root ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
